.SH "NAME"
odgi_flatten \- generate linearization of the graph
.SH "SYNOPSIS"
.sp
\fBodgi flatten\fP [\fB\-i, \-\-idx\fP=\fIFILE\fP] [\fIOPTION\fP]...
.SH "DESCRIPTION"
.sp
The odgi flatten(1) command projects the graph sequence and paths into FASTA and BED.
.SH "OPTIONS"
.SS "Graph Files IO"
.sp
\fB\-i, \-\-idx\fP=\fIFILE\fP
.RS 4
File containing the succinct variation graph to flatten. The file name usually ends with \fI.og\fP.
.RE
.SS "Output Options"
.sp
\fB\-f, \-\-fasta\fP=\fIFILE\fP
.RS 4
Write the concatenated node sequences in FASTA format to \fIFILE\fP.
.RE
.sp
\fB\-n, \-\-name\-seq\fP=\fISTRING\fP
.RS 4
The name to use for the concatenated graph sequence. Default is the name of the input file which was specified via [\fB\-i, \-\-idx\fP=\fIFILE\fP].
.RE
.sp
\fB\-b, \-\-bed\fP=\fIFILE\fP
.RS 4
Write the mapping between graph paths and the linearized FASTA sequence in BED format to \fIFILE\fP.
.RE
.SS "Program Information"
.sp
\fB\-h, \-\-help\fP
.RS 4
Print a help message for \fBodgi flatten\fP.
.RE
.SH "EXIT STATUS"
.sp
\fB0\fP
.RS 4
Success.
.RE
.sp
\fB1\fP
.RS 4
